{"key":"post-8522849","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>8522849</id>\n<content>Guys, cased rye makes an excellent fruiting substrate.&amp;nbsp; In fact, it's probably second only to brf cakes in BE.&amp;nbsp; Tapered, small mouth jars are also perfect for rye berries.&amp;nbsp; Bang them against a fully inflated tire or tree trunk, phone book, etc., to break the grains up, and then they can be poured out of the jar like sand.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Rye by definition isn't a bulk substrate.&amp;nbsp; It can be cased and fruited directly with excellent performance, or it can be used as spawn to a bulk substrate such as manure, coir, straw, etc.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>8522882</next>\n<prev>8522799</prev>\n<first>8522728</first>\n<last>8523334</last>\n<when>1213455650</when>\n<utime>06/14/08 06:00 PM</utime>\n</post>"}